          1. How to Test Your Scroll Wheel
        </h4>
        <p>
          Simply place your mouse cursor inside the dashed <strong>Scroll Wheel Test Zone</strong> and rotate your scroll wheel or swipe with two fingers on your trackpad. The indicators will instantly reflect active input direction, tick count, and velocity.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. Interpreting the Classification</h4>
        <p>
          Our classification algorithm assesses the distribution of your scroll deltas:
          <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1 mt-1">
            <li><strong>Notched Wheel:</strong> Repeated identical or large discrete steps (e.g., absolute values around 120 or 3).</li>
            <li><strong>Smooth/Trackpad Input:</strong> Highly variable, fractional, or continuous small delta inputs.</li>
          </ul>
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">3. Visualizing Errors on the Timeline</h4>
        <p>
          A healthy notched scroll wheel should produce consistent spacing between peaks on the timeline. If you experience erratic peaks, missing ticks, or spontaneous directional reversals while scrolling in one direction, your mouse wheel's hardware encoder may be failing or require cleaning.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">4. Data Export</h4>
